main event: Multiple sightings of unidentified flying objects (UFOs) in different locations and dates, including Puerto Rico and Roswell, New Mexico.
interesting points: The sighting in Puerto Rico described a 'disc-like object' that was concluded to be one of the FSU test balloons, rising to a high altitude and descending at a high rate of speed.

A pilot and 4 crew members sighted an unidentified object at 55,000 feet while flying a B-36 aircraft. The object moved from the 10 o'clock position to the 12 o'clock position without evasive action taken.
The report on the material found near Roswell, New Mexico, described the material as paper thin, tough, flexible, and glossy, with metallic properties, yet not magnetic or electrically conductive.
The material found near Roswell could not be torn, cut, pierced, burned, or deformed, and it exhibited a dull gray color composed of an unknown substance.
An object described as hexagonal in shape and constructed of a metal-like substance, resembling tinfoil, was recovered by personnel from the Roswell Army Air Field in 1947.
witnesses: Col. Wesley Davies, other officers, pilot, crew members, master sergeant
